The Universities of Lancaster and Central=20
Lancashire have the honour of jointly-organizing=20
the

30th Annual Conference of the
International Computer Archive for Modern and Medieval English.

The 30th ICAME conference will be held in Lancaster, UK
- one of the founding institutions of ICAME -
from 27-31 May 2009.

The focus of the conference in our special=20
anniversary year will be the achievements of the=20
corpus linguistics community to date, and the=20
challenges that the ICAME community believe have=20
yet to be faced.

The conference will thus be entitled: Looking back - moving forward.


*******************************************************************
Sign-up for second circular
If you wish to receive future announcements about ICAME 30,
please sign up to our notification list online:
http://www.icame30.info/signup.html.
*******************************************************************


Conference Venue
The conference will be held at Lancaster House=20
Hotel, a 4-star hotel located adjacent to=20
Lancaster University campus. We have also booked=20
a limited number of ensuite rooms in nearby=20
student accommodation. Registration and=20
information on conference costs will appear in a=20
second circular and on our website towards the=20
end of 2008: http://www.icame30.info/

Academic Programme
The program will consist of full papers,=20
work-in-progress reports, a poster session,=20
software demonstrations and a discussion panel,=20
as well as invited plenary talks. The following=20
speakers have already agreed to give plenaries at=20
the conference:

- Nick Ellis (University of Michigan)
- Yueguo Gu (Chinese Academy of Social Sciences)
- Geoffrey Pullum (University of Edinburgh)

In addition, there will be a plenary event by=20
Stig Johansson and Geoffrey Leech, commemorating=20
the history of ICAME on the occasion of its 30th=20
meeting.
A discussion panel on "Issues in Historical=20
Corpus Linguistics" will be chaired by Christian=20
Mair. There will also be pre-conference workshops=20
on "Errors and disfluencies in spoken corpora"=20
(Convenors: Sylvie de Cock and Ga=EBtanelle=20
Gilquin) and "Corpora and SLA" (Convenors: Ute=20
R=F6mer, Nick Ellis and Fanny Meunier).

Social Programme
There will be an excursion to the Lake District=20
on Friday afternoon, followed by a dinner on Lake=20
Windermere. There will be an opportunity to=20
indulge in fell-walking and to visit famous=20
literary sites. A post-conference excursion to=20
the remarkable eighth-century Ruthwell Cross=20
(with its runic inscription dating from the=20
earliest Old English) will be organised by=20
Geoffrey Leech. In addition, there will also be=20
an opportunity for some attendees of the=20
conference to visit the Hesketh Collection held=20
in the rare book archive of Lancaster University=20
Library.

Call for abstracts
Individual papers will be allowed 30 minutes,=20
including 10 minutes for discussion;=20
work-in-progress reports will be 15 minutes long,=20
including 5 minutes for discussion. The deadline=20
for abstract submission is 15th December 2008.=20
Abstracts of 400-600 words in length should be=20
submitted online at=20
http://www.icame30.info/abstracts.html. On the=20
form, please indicate whether your contribution=20
is a paper, a work-in-progress report, a poster=20
or a software demonstration. All abstracts will=20
be blind reviewed; notifications of acceptance=20
will be sent out by 15th January 2009. Deadline=20
for registration is 1st March 2009.

The local organising committee consists of:
Dawn Archer
Andrew Hardie
Sebastian Hoffmann (chair)
Geoffrey Leech
Paul Rayson
Anne Wichmann
e-mail: contact@icame30.info

-- 

